HID with the colour coding indicating the different spectral states."
"The HID track of MAXI J1631-472 follows a diagonal transi-
tion during the rise of the outburst when the spectral state changes
from hard to soft and is similar to those seen in systems such as GRO
J1655â€“40 and XTE J1550â€“564 (e.g. Russell et al. 2010; Uttley &
Klein-Wolt 2015). Some systems follow a canonical â€™qâ€™-shaped
HID pattern where the rise in X-ray flux from quiescence to peak
happens in the hard state and the system changes to intermediate
and then to soft at roughly constant peak flux. The differences in
the shapes of the HIDs have been suggested to be due to inclination
angle differences, with the â€™qâ€™-shaped HIDs occurring in low incli-
nation systems (ğ‘– 6 60â—¦ MuÃ±oz-Darias et al. 2013). This suggests
that the orbit of MAXI J1631-472 is possibly highly inclined."
3.3 Radio flaring
"The strongest radio emission from MAXI J1631-472 occurred
shortly after the transition from the intermediate to the soft X-
ray state. This is broadly in agreement with the unified picture put
forward in Fender et al. (2004). The three weeks or more of bright
radio emission hints at multiple flaring events, since flares from
X-ray binaries tend to evolve on shorter timescales (e.g. Fender &
Bright 2019), and these shorter timescale radio flares may them-
selves be the superposition of multiple events which can only be
discriminated at mm/IR frequencies (e.g. Tetarenko et al. 2017) or
with Very Long Baseline Interferometry (VLBI; e.g. Miller-Jones
et al. 2019). There may also be a contribution from physically sepa-
rated ejecta which are fading only slowly due to jet-ISM interactions"
"leading to in situ particle acceleration (see for example Bright et al.
2020). Such emission can persist for many months, fading slowly,
which is the most likely explanation for the persistent low level ra-
dio emission throughout the soft state. This component, originating
in ejecta completely separated from the core may potentially con-
tribute to the radio flux measured from the source after its return to
the hard state (see further discussion in section 3.4)."
"Assuming that the radio flare peak was due to a transition from
optically thick to thin emission as the ejecta expanded, we may
use the single-frequency estimates of the physical parameters from
Fender & Bright (2019) (their equations 28 â€“ 31). For a distance
of 5 kpc, at a peak flux density of 40 mJy at 1.4 GHz, we find a
corresponding physical radius at peak of ğ‘… = 3 Ã— 1013cm, corre-
sponding to a minimum internal energy of ğ¸ = 4 Ã— 1038 erg sâˆ’1,
a magnetic field of ğµ =âˆ¼ 0.2 G and a resulting brightness temper-
ature of ğ‘‡ğµ = 5 Ã— 1010 K. The dependence on distance ğ‘‘ of these
estimates are different for each quantity: ğ‘… âˆ ğ‘‘16/17, ğ¸ âˆ ğ‘‘40/17,
ğµ âˆ ğ‘‘âˆ’4/17 and ğ‘‡ğµ âˆ ğ‘‘2/17 (Fender & Bright 2019). These es-
timates are reasonable in the context of other X-ray binaries and
rather typical of a low-mass X-ray binary (and notably consider-
ably less powerful than the most luminous jet sources such as GRS
